Title = {{Vulnerability of East Asian bumblebee species to future climate and land
   cover changes}},
Journal = {{AGRICULTURE ECOSYSTEMS \& ENVIRONMENT}},
Year = {{2019}},
Volume = {{277}},
Pages = {{11-20}},
Month = {{MAY 1}},
Abstract = {{Pollinators play a key role in agricultural and natural ecosystems, but
   their biodiversity is highly vulnerable to the impact of environmental
   changes. Here, we evaluated the distributional responses of 29 bumblebee
   species endemic to East Asia to future (2050s and 2070s) climate and
   land cover changes, and 17-27 (59-93 \%) of the species exhibited range
   contraction. A decrease in species richness from 25 to 19 species in the
   highest region of central China was also detected due to range shifts of
   17?km to 574 km. Furthermore, one (3.44\%), three to five (10-17 \%),
   and two to eight (7-28 \%) of the 29 bumblebee species were predicted to
   become critically endangered, endangered and vulnerable in the future,
   respectively. Our study highlights the strong impact of environmental
   changes on species distributions, and we suggest strategies for the
   conservation of vulnerable species that include protecting the regions
   of high species richness and the most dominant land covers within the
   current range to mitigate the threat of environmental changes.}},
